msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:149: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:7880
msgid ""
"Use this function to get the regulatory rule for a specific frequency on a "
"given wireless device. If the device has a specific regulatory domain it "
"wants to follow we respect that unless a country IE has been received and "
"processed already."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:149: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:7886
msgid ""
"A valid pointer, or, when an error occurs, for example if no rule can be "
"found, the return value is encoded using ERR_PTR(). Use IS_ERR() to check "
"and PTR_ERR() to obtain the numeric return value. The numeric return value "
"will be -ERANGE if we determine the given center_freq does not even have a "
"regulatory rule for a frequency range in the center_freq's band. See "
"freq_in_rule_band() for our current definition of a band -- this is purely "
"subjective and right now it's 802.11 specific."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211.rst:156
msgid "RFkill integration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:158: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:8452
msgid ""
"RFkill integration in cfg80211 is almost invisible to drivers, as cfg80211 "
"automatically registers an rfkill instance for each wireless device it knows "
"about. Soft kill is also translated into disconnecting and turning all "
"interfaces off. Drivers are expected to turn off the device when all "
"interfaces are down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:158: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:8458
msgid ""
"However, devices may have a hard RFkill line, in which case they also need "
"to interact with the rfkill subsystem, via cfg80211. They can do this with a "
"few helper functions documented here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:161: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:8481
msgid "start polling rfkill"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../driver-api/80211/cfg80211:161: ../include/net/cfg80211.h:8487
